;dpr=2\"/\u003e\n                    \n                    \u003cimg width=\"2160\" height=\"1215\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" alt=\"HORI Split Pad Pro Attachment Set\" data-img-url=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/copy-of-169-6.png\" src=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/copy-of-169-6.png\"/\u003e\n        \n    \u003c/picture\u003e\n                                    \n    \u003c/figure\u003e\n\n\n        \u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThese Joy-Con replacements are quite substantial when compared to the originals, offering a beefier hand grip that can be more comfortable if you\u0026#39;re someone that plays in handheld mode for hours at a time.\u003c/p\u003e    \u003cp\u003eThe great part is that it isn\u0026#39;t just the grips that gain enhancements, but the buttons, analog sticks, triggers, and shoulder buttons also get substantial size improvements as well, making it more comfortable to play overall. \u003c/p\u003e    \u003cp\u003eIn addition, Hori also adds some nice perks to its controllers with assignable rear triggers and turbo functionality. You can even use this as a wired controller thanks to an included attachment. However, it\u0026#39;s important to note that there are trade-offs here.\u003c/p\u003e    \u003cp\u003eThe Hori system does not include motion controls, rumble, NFC or an IR camera. With that said, these are going to be an excellent replacement for standard Joy-Cons if you\u0026#39;re looking to get something that\u0026#39;s more comfortable.\u003c/p\u003e    \u003cp\u003eOf course, you\u0026#39;ll still have your original Joy-Con controllers just in case you need some of the more expanded features. Just be sure to pick these up while they\u0026#39;re on sale because a deal like this doesn\u0026#39;t come along all that often. \u003c/p\u003e    \u003c/div\u003e\n    \n                \n        \n        \n\n\n        \n\n\n\n\n\n                               